Can BC afford to set up a loss and damages fund? The answer is a resounding yes. In a recent report, @CCPA_BC's  @1alexhemingway found that if the province wants to increase public spending to tackle big challenges, it has the economic capacity to do so. https://t.co/oAOqoRsZbE

If BC were to explore a loss and damages fund, it would be more than just compensation—it could support First Nations in their self-determined efforts to rebuild their communities and make them resilient for the future.
A loss and damages fund akin to what was negotiated at COP27 could help BC fulfil its moral obligation of acknowledging the vast inequities of the climate crisis.
And there can be no doubt that #BC, as an oil and gas exporting province in one of the countries with the highest per capita and historic emissions in the world, has contributed to climate change.

We can find parallels to the realities of #FirstNations here in BC. Although they have contributed the least to climate change, they are already suffering the most severe impacts and will likely continue to do so as climate impacts worsen. https://t.co/yLxsmNbBS4

This is why the loss and damages fund is seen as one of the few successes to emerge from COP27. The idea is that countries that have historically contributed the most to climate change will "compensate" those that have contributed the least.

For 30 years, so-called developing countries have asked for a loss and damages fund to help them deal with the unavoidable economic, cultural and human losses attributed to climate change. And for 30 years, so-called developed nations have refused to entertain such talks.

- it raises questions over public authorities’ accountability for complying with obligations set in climate legislation- it raises procedural questions concerning citizens’ access to courts to challenge government’s climate action
The Finnish case is internationally interesting, because:- it tests effectiveness of climate legislation

"The applicants in the Finnish climate case argue that the Government breached the Climate Change Act by failing both to properly assess the need for additional measures and to take a decision on the need to adopt such measures."

"While information on the collapse of the forest carbon sink was already available at the time and the Government had taken some steps to address the situation, the report failed to recognise the need for additional measures and to analyse the situation in detail."

The Climate Change act dictates to adopt long- and mid-term climate plans, adaptation plan and a climate plan for the LULUCF sector, report on progress annually and suggest additional measures if needed. This years report did not suggest additional measures...
"Finland’s Medium-term Climate Plan and the LULUCF Sector Climate Plan are based on the assumption that the LULUCF sector remains a carbon sink of 21 million tons of carbon dioxide equivalent."

Reasons: "In 2021, felling reached the exceptionally high level of 76,3 million cubic meters of stemwood, the second largest ever recorded in Finland.""At the same time, forest growth in Finland decreased by a total of 4.3 million cubic metres year on year."

"Finland’s 2021 greenhouse gas inventory data, released in December 2022, confirmed that in 2021 Finland’s LULUCF sector released an equivalent of 0,9 million tons of carbon dioxide from the atmosphere, while in 2020 it removed more than 9, 2 million tons of carbon dioxide."

These protective reserves are critical for the future of species. Refugia in general “harbor large amounts of genetic diversity, so I guess that gives some hope,” said biologist Matthew Koski at Clemson University.

Scientists around the world have been locating existing refugia and tallying their various soil types, water availability and slope direction, all of which play a role in creating nurturing microclimates. https://t.co/2qnZibVQZ6

But farms like Birmingham’s might help counter that trend at a time when climate change is accelerating the threat to species. Data show that the best climate-mitigating effect comes from a mosaic of landscape types, with more greenery producing greater benefits.

The UN Environment Program found that food and agriculture currently drive 70 percent of species loss, through deforestation, grassland conversion, chemical use and other changes to the landscape. https://t.co/ui03yLsXCP

In fact, refugia have played a critical role in protecting species before during the last Ice Age. Researchers are now looking at ways this might work in our age of rising temperatures, and the role that farms might play in enhancing biodiversity.

Birmingham's property has the hallmarks of a refugium. Refugia, from the Latin for shelter and first used in biology in the 1940s, are viewed as “relatively buffered” from climate change and a haven for vulnerable species.

That’s why USDA and conservation nonprofits encourage farmers to plant buffers like pollinator strips. (Birmingham got help from both.) But there may be more going on between Birmingham’s plants and bees in this era of climate change. https://t.co/Vlj5JVz3mR

There’s plenty of research that supports Birmingham’s experience of wild bees’ relevance in pollinating crops like tree fruits, blueberries, and cranberries, and the role diverse plantings play in giving bees a needed forage and habitat boost. https://t.co/qPFkyXBVcF

Honeybees, which are trucked in to perform this task on orchards around the nation, were nowhere to be found. To her surprise, though, local wild pollinators like bumble, sweat, and mason bees did all the pollination work. The result: a bountiful apple crop. https://t.co/q03R7U9nF7

Two decades later, on June 14, 2022, the weather turned unseasonably hot. According to Birmingham, “We had this record-breaking heat and the trees just fast-forwarded into blossom…" She worried that, with so many choices, the wild bees might skip her orchard’s 16,000 trees. https://t.co/Vyb2p3NJT1

In 2002, Deirdre Birmingham and her husband, John Biondi, bought a 166-acre farm in southwestern Wisconsin’s Driftless region. They knew this would benefit beleaguered wild bees but they weren’t fully aware how this decision to rewild their landscape would help the farm, too.

@Ahhmard Teaching a sustainability course this semester and I have been exposed to some attitudes we humans have that literally destroys the planet.
It is important for everyone to understand the seriousness of global warming and take action to address it. We only have one planet, and it is up to all of us to protect it for future generations.

In addition to these efforts, individuals can take simple steps in their daily lives to help combat global warming. These include reducing energy consumption at home, using public transportation or carpooling.

We can also support policies and regulations that encourage businesses to reduce their carbon emissions and invest in sustainable practices. Governments can also invest in research and development to create new technologies that can help reduce greenhouse gas emissions.

The good news is that we can take action to mitigate the effects of global warming. We can reduce our carbon footprint by using renewable energy sources, such as wind and solar power, and by reducing our consumption of fossil fuels.

The consequences of global warming are far-reaching and devastating. They include the loss of biodiversity, the extinction of species, and the displacement of millions of people as a result of rising sea levels and extreme weather events.

The effects of global warming are already being felt around the world. Climate change is causing more frequent and severe heat waves, droughts, floods, and storms. It is also leading to the melting of glaciers and ice caps, which is causing sea levels to rise.

The primary cause of global warming is the burning of fossil fuels, which releases carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gases into the atmosphere. These gases trap heat from the sun, causing the Earth's temperature to rise.

By the way, don't confuse "tech" with "science".There's a lot of so-called "climate tech" out there that has absolutely no connection to climate science or the physics of how this planet actually works. To fix the problems of the planet, you need to know how the planet works.

We must act with extreme urgency, but also laser-focused accuracy. We cannot waste one moment, or one dollar, in the quest to stop climate change and build a more verdant, equitable, and sustainable world.And science will point us in the right direction.

My advice to anyone who wants to help address climate change: learn the basics of the science and make sure you include scientists on your team.Way too much work is happening, and way too many dollars invested, without any science in the room.That's a mistake.

While we need all of society involved in stopping climate change, science has an instrumental role to play. Always.It discovered the problem.It told us what the effective solutions were. (And the not-so-effective ones.)And now it has given us a roadmap for the future.

So that's why we developed the Drawdown Roadmap -- as a guide to the world for climate action.We will officially release the Roadmap in the coming months, but here is a short presentation that gives the basics.https://t.co/DTId8FVZyj

Unfortunately, without a good roadmap, governments, businesses, investors, and philanthropists tend to invest in fads and hype -- not the best solutions and strategies.We need science to tell us when, where, and how to adopt, scale, and deploy solutions.

That's what the new Drawdown Roadmap is all about.The Drawdown Roadmap points to which climate actions we should prioritize — across sectors, timescales, and geographies — to make the most of efforts to stop climate change.

But knowing there is a *problem* isn't enough.And presenting a suite of *potential solutions* isn't enough either.Science has to do more.  It has to present a roadmap to the future, showing *how* we can implement solutions over time.

We have updated our library of effective climate solutions several times since then, and the latest results can be found here.These are the solutions that work. They are rigorously examined and tested.  And they can help address climate change today.https://t.co/6W4spFK4Pk

Second, science has helped us understand the suite of solutions we have to address climate change.Our organization, Project Drawdown, was a pioneer in this field, and was the first to catalog nearly 100 effective solutions to the climate crisis back in 2017.
So you can thank science for the heads up.If it weren't for decades of dedicated research, we wouldn't have any idea what's happening.  And we wouldn't even begin to know what to do about it.

Since then, especially during the last few decades, climate science has matured into a very sophisticated field, able to understand and predict the behavior of our planet in astonishing detail.And it is absolutely clear that we humans are changing the climate.
Sadly, as a woman scientist in the 19th century, she was not given due credit. Until recently.
